content.text:
The issue was caused by `IndentationRule` creating a new indentation context for nested qualified expressions (specifically when mixing `DOT_QUALIFIED_EXPRESSION` and `SAFE_ACCESS_EXPRESSION`), even though they are part of the same call chain. This caused the indentation level to be calculated incorrectly in certain newline scenarios, leading to false positive errors where the rule expected less indentation than what is standard (e.g. in IntelliJ IDEA).

I fixed this by modifying `IndentationRule.kt` to prevent starting a new indentation context if the node is a `DOT_QUALIFIED_EXPRESSION` or `SAFE_ACCESS_EXPRESSION` and its parent is also one of these types. This ensures that the entire chain shares the same indentation context.

I verified the fix by creating a reproduction test case that mirrored the reported issue, confirming it failed before the fix and passed after. I also ran the existing `IndentationRuleTest` to ensure no regressions were introduced.

**Files modified:**
- `ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/IndentationRule.kt`

